    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1870-09-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1870-09-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="161"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d161">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">No. 161.</note>
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. Bancroft</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                        Fish</persName>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 135.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation,</hi>
                            <hi rend="italic"> Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1870-09-16">
                            <hi rend="italic">September</hi> 16, 1870</date>. (Received October
                        3.)</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> Having received a telegram from Commander Luce,
                    of the Juniata, that the French blockade of the Elbe and Weser had been raised
                    on the 11th, I telegraphed the news to you yesterday.</p>
                <p>To-day I have to inform you that the French steamer Pereire, which on its voyage
                    from New York touched at Brest, had on board for Havre a considerable number of
                    Remington guns. This fact is also known to the government here. * * * * *</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>GEO. BANCROFT.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
